******************************************************************************************************************************
Challenge 1: Too many concurrent users
******************************************************************************************************************************

I use a global + local load balancer combination. Global for geographic routing — sends users to nearest data center. 
Local for distributing within that data center across servers. The tradeoff is added latency at the routing layer,
but the availability gain outweighs that for large scale systems. The risk is the load balancer itself becoming a single point 
of failure — which you solve with redundant LBs in active-passive configuration.

******************************************************************************************************************************
Challenge 2: Too many writes
******************************************************************************************************************************

Use Buffer of Message queues


General things to know:
1. Monolithic vs Microservices architecture
2. Vertical scaling 
3. Horizontal scaling
4. Sharding/ partitioning
5. Separate Read/Write systems (Social media: Read heavy, IoT system: Write heavy)
6. Use relational databases when consistency is critical. Financial transactions, inventory management, and user account systems 
require accurate, structured data. NoSQL offers flexibility. Relational databases offer guarantees.
7. Use NoSQL when data structure varies by record
8. Caching => LRU, LFU, TTL for expiration [Longer TTL means stale data but less database load. Shorter TTL means fresher data but more database hits.]
9. CDNs for static assets: images, videos, CSS, JavaScript files
10. Messaging Queues for: Communication between components; Storage/Processing of messages; Retry failed messages 
=> Tibco, ActiveMQ, RabbitMQ, Kafka, AWS SQS 
11. API Gateway => For Authentication, Rate limiting 

******************************************************************************************************************************
Use of Caching is more preferred for READ flows, than write.
******************************************************************************************************************************

Why Write Flow Skips Cache
Write flow reality:
User shortens a URL → maybe never visits it again
User shortens a URL → shares it → visited 1000x tomorrow

You dont know which one it is at write time.
So if you cache on every write:
1 Million URLs created today
→ Cache all 1 million immediately
→ 80% never get clicked
→ Cache full of useless entries
→ Actually popular URLs get evicted
→ Cache miss rate goes UP not down
You have wasted cache space on URLs nobody visits.

The Better Strategy — Lazy Population
Write  → DB only (always happens)
First read → cache miss → DB → populate cache
Second read → cache hit (now it earned its place)
Cache only fills with URLs people actually visit. This is called lazy loading or read-through caching.
Popular URL  → gets cached naturally after first read
               → all subsequent reads served from cache ✅

Unpopular URL → sits in DB only
               → never wastes cache space ✅

The One Exception
Pre-warming the cache.
If you KNOW a URL will go viral immediately —
marketing campaign, product launch, Super Bowl ad —
you can manually write to cache at creation time.

tiny.url/superbowl → cache immediately on write
But this is a special case, not the default flow.

